In this example, `owner_string` is the owner of the string value "Hello, world!", and `borrowed_string` is a borrowed reference to that value.

When you're done using the toy and want to give it back, you might say "Here you go, you can have your toy back now". Similarly, in Rust, borrowed references are automatically returned to their owner when they go out of scope. This means that when the borrowed reference is no longer needed, Rust will automatically return it to the owner.

For example, in the previous example, when `borrowed_string` goes out of scope, Rust will automatically return the borrowed reference to `owner_string`. You don't need to do anything explicitly to give it back.

So, in summary, borrowing in Rust is done using the `&` symbol to borrow a reference to a value owned by someone else, and borrowed references are automatically returned to their owner when they go out of scope.

Sure, I'd be happy to explain how `to_owned()` works with toys using the same toy analogy.

In Rust, the `to_owned()` method is used to create an owned copy of a borrowed value. This is similar to how you might make a copy of a toy that you borrowed from someone, so that you can have your own version of the toy to play with.

For example, imagine that your friend owns a toy car, and you want to borrow it to play with. Your friend might lend you the toy car, but they still own it. If you want to have your own version of the toy car that you can keep and play with whenever you want, you could make a copy of the toy car and keep it for yourself.

Similarly, in Rust, if you have a borrowed reference to a value that someone else owns, you can create an owned copy of that value using the `to_owned()` method. This creates a new value that you own, so you can modify it or keep it for as long as you want without affecting the original value.

Here's an example of how `to_owned()` works in Rust:


```rust
fn main() {
 let original\_string = String::from("Hello, world!");
 let borrowed\_string = &original_string;
 let owned\_string = borrowed_string.to\_owned();

 println!("Original: {}", original_string);
 println!("Borrowed: {}", borrowed_string);
 println!("Owned: {}", owned_string);
}
```
In this example, `original_string` is the owner of the string value "Hello, world!", and `borrowed_string` is a borrowed reference to that value. We then use the `to_owned()` method to create an owned copy of the value, which is assigned to the variable `owned_string`.

When we print out the values, we can see that `original_string` and `borrowed_string` still refer to the same value, while `owned_string` is a new value that we own:


```makefile
Original: Hello, world!
Borrowed: Hello, world!
Owned: Hello, world!
```
So, to summarize, `to_owned()` in Rust is similar to making a copy of a toy that you borrowed from someone, so that you can have your own version of the toy to play with. In Rust, `to_owned()` creates an owned copy of a borrowed value, so that you can modify it or keep it for as long as you want without affecting the original value.

